  "text": "This analysis identifies all key Rust source files implementing edition-specific import path handling between Rust editions 2015, 2018, and 2021 (with 2024 support), focusing on three critical areas:\n\n## 1. Edition-Specific Prelude Module Exports (v1 vs edition-versioned)\n\nThe prelude system is implemented across two main library crates:\n\n**Standard Library (std):** library/std/src/prelude/mod.rs exports four edition-specific prelude modules:\n- `pub mod rust_2015` - Uses the base v1 prelude\n- `pub mod rust_2018` - Uses the base v1 prelude (same as 2015)\n- `pub mod rust_2021` - Re-exports v1, then additionally imports `core::prelude::rust_2021` to add `TryFrom`, `TryInto`, and `FromIterator` traits\n- `pub mod rust_2024` - Re-exports v1 and core::prelude modules, adding `Future` and `IntoFuture` to the 2021 base\n\nLibrary/std/src/prelude/v1.rs serves as the base prelude (used in 2015 and 2018) and re-exports core items from both `core::prelude::v1` and standard library types (Box, Vec, String, ToOwned).\n\n**Core Library (core):** library/core/src/prelude/mod.rs mirrors this structure:\n- `pub mod rust_2015` - Uses v1\n- `pub mod rust_2018` - Uses v1\n- `pub mod rust_2021` - Adds `TryFrom`, `TryInto`, `FromIterator` to the v1 base\n- `pub mod rust_2024` - Extends 2021 with `Future` and `IntoFuture`\n\nLibrary/core/src/prelude/v1.rs exports core traits and types like Clone, Copy, Debug, Drop, Fn, FnMut, FnOnce, From, Into, Option, Result, Iterator, and all built-in macros.\n\n## 2. Edition-Based Macro_use Difference and Prelude Injection\n\nCompiler/rustc_builtin_macros/src/standard_library_imports.rs contains the `inject()` function that automatically adds prelude imports to every crate. This function directly demonstrates edition-specific path handling:\n\n```rust\nlet import_path = root\n    .iter()\n    .chain(&[name, sym::prelude])\n    .chain(&[match edition {\n        Edition2015 => sym::rust_2015,\n        Edition2018 => sym::rust_2018,\n        Edition2021 => sym::rust_2021,\n        Edition2024 => sym::rust_2024,\n        EditionFuture => sym::rust_future,\n    }])\n```\n\nFor 2015 edition, the path starts with `kw::PathRoot` (creating `::std::prelude::rust_2015::*`), while 2018+ editions use relative imports (`std::prelude::rust_2018::*`). Additionally, when edition >= 2018, the `ident_span` uses `span` rather than `call_site`, affecting macro hygiene.\n\nThe macro_use prelude is defined in compiler/rustc_resolve/src/lib.rs as `macro_use_prelude: FxIndexMap<Symbol, NameBinding<'ra>>`. The difference is critical: in edition 2015, the MacroUsePrelude scope is always visited (rust_2015 == true condition at line 160 of ident.rs), whereas in 2018+, it's only visited when `use_prelude` is true and not suppressed by `#[no_implicit_prelude]`.\n\n## 3. Resolver Behavior Changes for Edition 2015 vs 2018+ (Uniform Paths)\n\nCompiler/rustc_resolve/src/ident.rs line 115-160 reveals critical edition-specific scope resolution:\n\n```rust\nlet rust_2015 = ctxt.edition().is_rust_2015();\n// ...\nScope::MacroUsePrelude => use_prelude || rust_2015,\n```\n\nThis means 2015 edition always includes MacroUsePrelude in scope resolution, supporting mixed import modes where both old-style (`::foo`) and new-style paths coexist.\n\nCompiler/rustc_resolve/src/lib.rs (lines 436-443) defines three critical virtual modules for path resolution:\n- `ModuleAndExternPrelude(Module)` - Used for `::foo` paths from 2015 edition macros in 2018+ crates (backward compatibility)\n- `ExternPrelude` - Used in 2018+ editions for absolute `::` paths\n- These represent the key architectural difference: 2015 treats `::` as crate-root relative (with fallback to extern prelude), while 2018+ treats it as extern-prelude only\n\nCompiler/rustc_resolve/src/diagnostics.rs (lines 2480-2485) and imports.rs (line 182-183) confirm this:\n```\n// ::foo is mounted at the crate root for 2015, and is the extern\n// prelude for 2018+\n```\n\n## 4. Edition 2021 Prelude Collisions and Lints\n\nCompiler/rustc_lint_defs/src/builtin.rs defines RUST_2021_PRELUDE_COLLISIONS and RUST_2024_PRELUDE_COLLISIONS lints to detect when user-defined traits would conflict with newly-added prelude items.\n\nCompiler/rustc_hir_typeck/src/method/prelude_edition_lints.rs implements `check_for_ambiguous_method_calls()` to detect methods like `try_into()`, `try_from()`, and `from_iter()` that will become ambiguous in 2021 when the traits are added to the prelude.\n\nTests in tests/ui/rust-2021/future-prelude-collision*.rs verify this behavior, showing how code that compiles in 2018 with custom TryInto traits becomes ambiguous in 2021.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe edition migration is implemented through:\n1. **Separate prelude modules per edition** with incremental additions (2021 adds TryFrom/TryInto/FromIterator; 2024 adds Future/IntoFuture)\n2. **Edition-aware path resolution** in the resolver where 2015 paths fall back through module/extern-prelude while 2018+ paths target extern-prelude directly\n3. **Special handling of macro_use prelude** that's always accessible in 2015 but controlled by implicit_prelude flags in 2018+\n4. **Comprehensive linting** for ambiguous method calls that will break in future editions"
